      "solution": "#include <stdlib.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <string.h>\n#include <stdbool.h>\n\nint main ()\n{       \n    char buffer[101];\n    \n    gets(buffer);\n\n    int flg = 0;\n    int lon = strlen(buffer);\n    char newbuffer[104]={'\\0'};\n    char testbuffer[104]={'\\0'};\n    for (int i=0; i<26; i++)\n    {\n        testbuffer[0]=' ';\n        for (int j=0; j<lon; j++)\n        {\n            int a = buffer[j];\n            if ((a<91)&&(a>63))\n            {\n                a = a + i;\n                if (a>90) a = a - 26;\n            }\n            newbuffer[j] = a;\n            testbuffer[j+1] = a;\n            if (i==0) strcat(testbuffer, \" \");\n        }\n        char* ret = strstr(testbuffer, \" CHIEF \");\n        if (ret!=NULL)\n        {\n            printf(\"%s\", newbuffer);\n            flg = 1;\n        }\n    }\n    if (flg==0)\n    {\n        printf(\"WRONG MESSAGE\\n\");\n    }\n    \n    return 0;\n}\n",
      "statement": "During the galactic war against the Zorglons, the Earth Intelligence Agency intercepted a lot of messages.\n\nIt is your task to decode them.\n\nYou know that:\n1/ The messages are always in capital letters. Words are separated with white spaces. You do not have to decode these spaces.\n2/ They are coded with a Caesar cipher.\n3/ The Zorglons always include the word {{CHIEF}} in them to be sure there are true messages. Be careful, this must be a separate word: a message such as {{HANDKERCHIEF}} is not a true message.\n\nNote that the Caesar cipher is a shift in the alphabet: for example, with a right shift of 3, A becomes D, B becomes E... and Z becomes C (reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caesar_cipher).\n\nGiven a message, you must decode it (i.e. find the correct shift and output the text containing the word {{CHIEF}}) or output {{WRONG MESSAGE}} if it is not a true message.",
